                },
                {
                    "title": "<span style=\"font-size:26px\">&nbsp;</span>",
                    "content": "<div class=\"footnotes\">\n<h5>Footnotes</h5>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li>Work specialization within households has been a concept in economics since the proposal of the unitary family model by Gary Becker in his paper, <a href=\"https://www.jstor.org/stable/2228949\" target=\"_blank\">\u201cA Theory of the Allocation of Time\u201d (The Economic Journal, vol. 75, No. 299, 1965)</a>, including the argument of efficiency, later criticized by a number of feminist economists, including Bina Agarwal in her paper,<a href=\"http://www.binaagarwal.com/downloads/apapers/bagaining_and_gender_relations.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">\u201cBargaining\u201d and gender relations: within and beyond the household\u201d, Institute of Economic Growth, University of Delhi</a>. (<a data-storymaps=\"MJ-ACTION-1614876571134\" data-storymaps-type=\"navigate\">\u21e1 back to text</a>)</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n",
